---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost, description } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/guides/deliverability';
const title = 'Shopify Email Deliverability Tools: 14 Options and a Safer Pilot';
const desc = 'Compare 14 Shopify email deliverability and lifecycle tools by authentication, list hygiene, event control, pricing model, and implementation risk.';
const official: Record<string, string> = {
  klaviyo: 'https://www.klaviyo.com/features/deliverability', omnisend: 'https://www.omnisend.com/features/deliverability/', brevo: 'https://www.brevo.com/features/email-deliverability/',
  'shopify-email': 'https://www.shopify.com/email-marketing', drip: 'https://www.drip.com/features', sendlane: 'https://www.sendlane.com/features', activecampaign: 'https://www.activecampaign.com/email-marketing',
  mailchimp: 'https://mailchimp.com/features/email-marketing/', 'yotpo-email-sms': 'https://www.yotpo.com/products/email-sms/', privy: 'https://www.privy.com/features', postscript: 'https://postscript.io/sms-marketing',
  attentive: 'https://attentive.com/platform', aftership: 'https://www.aftership.com/email', tinyemail: 'https://tinyemail.com/features'
};
const entries = [
  ['klaviyo','Deep Shopify event and consent segmentation','Native event depth can make it easier to isolate purchasers, engaged recipients, and suppression states. Validate the actual event names, timestamps, catalog fields, and identity merge behavior in a test account before trusting a flow.','Best for teams with an owner for data and deliverability operations. Pros: mature ecommerce segmentation; detailed flow controls. Cons: profile-based billing can make cold-data retention expensive. Pricing caveat: confirm active-profile definitions, SMS credits, and deliverability services on the current plan.'],
  ['omnisend','Fast multichannel Shopify rollout','Omnisend is useful when a store needs email, SMS, and push paths coordinated around a small set of Shopify events. Its prebuilt journeys can shorten setup, but operators still need to inspect consent and recent-purchaser exclusions rather than assuming the template handles them.','Best for small and midsize stores shipping a few core journeys quickly. Pros: practical channel coordination; accessible templates. Cons: complex data governance may need workarounds. Pricing caveat: price contacts, email sends, SMS, and overages separately.'],
  ['brevo','Volume-aware email and transactional separation','Brevo suits a store that wants marketing email and transactional infrastructure considered together while keeping send volume visible. Test whether Shopify order, refund, and consent data arrives with enough detail for suppression; do not infer ecommerce depth from a successful connection alone.','Best for budget-sensitive programs with clear event contracts. Pros: send-volume pricing options; transactional capability. Cons: lighter Shopify-specific workflow depth. Pricing caveat: check email volume, contacts, SMS, dedicated IP, and transactional usage as separate line items.'],
  ['shopify-email','Native broadcasts with minimal moving parts','Shopify Email is a reasonable starting point for permissioned campaigns built inside Shopify Admin. It is not a substitute for a deliverability program: authentication, sunset rules, complaint monitoring, and transactional separation still need an operating owner.','Best for smaller stores sending straightforward campaigns. Pros: native catalog context; low implementation overhead. Cons: limited lifecycle and diagnostic depth. Pricing caveat: verify the included monthly allowance and current per-send rates before forecasting.'],
  ['drip','Behavioral workflows with explicit branches','Drip can fit operators who want to inspect a visual path from Shopify behavior to message and exit condition. Use a test matrix for browse, cart, purchase, refund, and unsubscribe events so a visually clear workflow does not conceal duplicate enrollment.','Best for hands-on ecommerce teams building custom branches. Pros: readable workflow logic; useful behavior triggers. Cons: per-person economics and setup effort need modeling. Pricing caveat: confirm billable people, inactive treatment, and add-ons at projected list size.'],
  ['sendlane','Guided ecommerce migration and operations','Sendlane is relevant when migration help and ecommerce-oriented automation matter as much as the editor. Ask for the migration scope in writing, then independently verify domain authentication, suppression import, Shopify timestamps, and rollback ownership.','Best for DTC teams buying onboarding alongside software. Pros: ecommerce focus; migration support may reduce operator load. Cons: pricing and services can be less self-serve. Pricing caveat: request a written quote covering contacts, sends, SMS, onboarding, and deliverability support.'],
  ['activecampaign','CRM and Shopify lifecycle overlap','ActiveCampaign is a candidate when Shopify orders feed a broader sales or CRM process. Keep marketing consent, sales follow-up, and transactional notices as separate states; a powerful automation builder cannot decide the lawful or customer-safe boundary for you.','Best for wholesale, high-consideration, or sales-assisted stores. Pros: conditional logic; CRM handoff. Cons: less Shopify-native than ecommerce specialists. Pricing caveat: tier, contacts, seats, and CRM features can all change total cost.'],
  ['mailchimp','Familiar campaigns and simple audiences','Mailchimp can work when the operating need is a small number of campaigns and a familiar publishing workflow. Before import, compare its audience model with Shopify customer states and confirm that unsubscribes, suppressions, and duplicate identities remain consistent.','Best for teams prioritizing familiarity over deep lifecycle control. Pros: broad editor and ecosystem; approachable campaign setup. Cons: generic ecommerce modeling; audience billing can grow. Pricing caveat: confirm contacts, audiences, transactional products, and plan-gated automation.'],
  ['yotpo-email-sms','Retention signals connected to reviews and loyalty','Yotpo Email & SMS is most relevant when reviews, loyalty, and messaging are already part of the retention stack. Pilot the handoff from review or loyalty state to email eligibility, and confirm that a customer’s channel permissions are not silently broadened by the suite.','Best for brands consolidating Yotpo modules. Pros: review and loyalty context; multichannel option. Cons: suite complexity and modular billing. Pricing caveat: price email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, and usage commitments independently.'],
  ['privy','Capture hygiene before lifecycle scaling','Privy’s value is strongest at acquisition: collecting consent and delivering a controlled welcome path. Treat popup conversion as an input, not a deliverability result; test consent language, source metadata, double-opt-in choices, and the suppression path into the sending platform.','Best for growing stores whose bottleneck is list capture. Pros: Shopify-native forms; quick capture experiments. Cons: shallower lifecycle diagnostics. Pricing caveat: pageviews, contacts, email, SMS, and feature limits may be separate.'],
  ['postscript','Permissioned SMS alongside email','Postscript belongs in a deliverability review when SMS is part of the recovery or campaign plan. Email permission does not authorize SMS: test keyword, checkout, opt-out, quiet-hour, and carrier-cost rules separately, then coordinate suppression across tools.','Best for SMS-led Shopify programs. Pros: SMS-specific compliance controls; two-way use cases. Cons: not an email replacement; usage costs can escalate. Pricing caveat: model message segments, carrier fees, credits, and consent-related tooling.'],
  ['attentive','Enterprise SMS and managed support','Attentive can fit a scaled DTC operation that needs enterprise SMS acquisition, orchestration, or managed services. Its fit should be judged through a written implementation plan: domain ownership, data retention, consent export, support response, and minimum commitments matter as much as features.','Best for larger teams with a dedicated channel owner. Pros: enterprise support and SMS depth. Cons: heavier implementation and custom commercial terms. Pricing caveat: request minimums, services, message fees, and exit terms in writing.'],
  ['aftership-email','Post-purchase communication and tracking context','AfterShip Email is relevant when delivery status and post-purchase education are the source of message relevance. Keep service updates distinct from promotional permission, and test carrier events, delay states, refund handling, and fallback behavior before counting post-purchase sends as marketing automation.','Best for stores prioritizing shipping communication. Pros: shipment context; useful post-purchase trigger. Cons: narrower lifecycle scope than an ESP. Pricing caveat: verify shipment volume, automation limits, branding, and marketing features separately.'],
  ['tinyemail','Lean campaigns with a smaller operating surface','tinyEmail may suit a small store that wants a lightweight campaign workflow and does not need a large event model. Validate Shopify sync, unsubscribe propagation, domain authentication, and reporting exports first; a low subscription price does not remove the cost of poor list hygiene.','Best for lean teams with simple campaign requirements. Pros: low operational complexity; approachable publishing. Cons: limited advanced diagnostics and event branching. Pricing caveat: check current contact, send, automation, and support ceilings rather than relying on old comparisons.']
].map(([slug,best,paragraph,tradeoffs], index) => ({ app: appBySlug(slug)!, best, paragraph, tradeoffs, official: official[slug], index })).filter((x) => x.app);

const faqs = [
  { question: 'What should a Shopify deliverability pilot prove?', answer: 'It should prove domain authentication, consent and unsubscribe propagation, event timestamps, suppression rules, duplicate prevention, complaint and bounce visibility, and a rollback path. Open rate alone is not enough evidence.' },
  { question: 'Should I choose a dedicated deliverability tool or an ESP?', answer: 'Start with the failure you can observe. If the problem is domain reputation or authentication, investigate the sending setup and monitoring. If the problem is audience state or duplicate automation, test the ESP and Shopify event contract. Do not buy a second tool before identifying the control gap.' },
  { question: 'Are vendor prices comparable?', answer: 'Not without a common forecast. Compare active profiles, monthly sends, SMS segments, transactional volume, inactive-contact treatment, onboarding, dedicated infrastructure, and overages using the same 90-day Shopify scenario.' }
];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24"><div class="container">
    <a class="link text-sm" href="/guides">← All operator guides</a>
    <p class="editorial-kicker mt-6">Shopify operator guide · Deliverability</p>
    <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Shopify email deliverability tools: choose the control you can prove</h1>
    <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-slate-700">Deliverability is an operating system, not a single app feature. Shopify stores need authenticated sending, permissioned acquisition, accurate purchase and refund events, suppression that travels across channels, and a measurement plan that separates placement signals from revenue claims.</p>
    <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-slate-600">The 14 options below are mapped to different jobs: ecommerce event depth, capture, SMS, transactional context, CRM, and lightweight campaigns. Product capabilities and prices change, so each official link is a verification prompt rather than evidence of a permanent feature or rate.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="container pb-14"><div class="ledger-card overflow-x-auto"><h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Shortlist by deliverability job</h2><table class="mt-6 w-full min-w-[900px] text-left text-sm"><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Best for</th><th>Primary proof</th><th>Cost question</th></tr></thead><tbody>{entries.map(({app,best,tradeoffs,official}) => <tr class="border-b border-cyan-900/10"><td class="py-3 pr-4"><a class="link font-bold" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{app.name}</a></td><td class="py-3 pr-4">{best}</td><td class="py-3 pr-4">{app.strengths?.[0] ?? 'event and suppression control'}</td><td class="py-3"><a class="link" href={official}>Verify plan →</a></td></tr>)}</tbody></table></div></section>

  <section class="container space-y-10 pb-16"><p class="editorial-kicker">Tool-by-tool fit</p><h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-slate-950">14 tools reviewed for Shopify deliverability work</h2>
    {entries.map(({app,best,paragraph,tradeoffs,official,index}) => <article class="card"><div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline justify-between gap-3"><h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-slate-950"><span class="text-cyan-800">{index + 1}.</span> {app.name}</h3><span class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-wide text-cyan-800">Best for: {best}</span></div><p class="mt-5 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">{paragraph}</p><p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-slate-700">{tradeoffs} Read the <a class="link" href={official}>official product information</a> and the internal <a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>{app.name} review</a> before committing.</p></article>)}
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-14"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Evidence to collect before launch</h2><table class="data-table mt-5"><thead><tr><th>Control</th><th>Test</th><th>Keep as evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Authentication</td><td>SPF, DKIM, DMARC alignment and branded return path</td><td>DNS record, provider status, DMARC report owner</td></tr><tr><td>Permission</td><td>Signup source, timestamp, channel, unsubscribe, suppression</td><td>Test profile event log and consent export</td></tr><tr><td>Shopify events</td><td>Signup, cart, purchase, fulfillment, refund, subscription</td><td>Payload, timestamp, identity, expected exit state</td></tr><tr><td>Reputation</td><td>Bounce, complaint, deferral and recipient-domain trend</td><td>Weekly baseline and incident notes</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section>

  <section class="container pb-14"><div class="ledger-card overflow-x-auto"><p class="editorial-kicker">14-day implementation pilot</p><h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-slate-950">Prove one flow before scaling sends</h2><table class="mt-6 w-full min-w-[800px] text-left text-sm"><thead><tr><th>Days</th><th>Work</th><th>Pass condition</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1–2</td><td>Choose welcome, cart, or post-purchase; document consent, owner, source events, exclusions, and rollback.</td><td>Flow spec and suppression map are signed off.</td></tr><tr><td>3–5</td><td>Authenticate the subdomain and send test profiles through signup, purchase, refund, unsubscribe, and duplicate identity.</td><td>Events arrive once, with correct timestamps and exits.</td></tr><tr><td>6–9</td><td>Run an engaged-only cohort; keep marketing, service, and SMS permissions separate.</td><td>No duplicate sends, consent crossover, or unexpected promotional messages.</td></tr><tr><td>10–12</td><td>Review bounce, complaint, deferral, domain-level placement signals, clicks, support tickets, and contribution margin.</td><td>Baseline and decision threshold are written; platform-attributed revenue is not treated as incremental proof.</td></tr><tr><td>13–14</td><td>Decide scale, revise, or stop; export configuration and record the next owner.</td><td>Rollback and suppression can be executed without vendor guesswork.</td></tr></tbody></table></div></section>

  <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify max-w-4xl"><h2>Practical rules for safe Shopify sending</h2><p>Authenticate before volume, but do not confuse authentication with inbox placement. Start with consented, recently engaged recipients; keep a pre-period or holdout where feasible; and investigate complaint, bounce, and deferral changes by recipient domain. Apple Mail privacy features make opens an incomplete signal, so pair them with clicks, purchases, unsubscribes, complaints, and margin.</p><p>Do not import a full customer export and call it a deliverability strategy. Retain the consent evidence you need, suppress people who should not receive marketing, and confirm that a refund or recent purchase exits a recovery flow. Email permission does not automatically grant SMS permission, and a shipping update should not become a promotional send without its own basis.</p><h2>Internal checks and official sources</h2><p>Use the <a class="link" href="/guides/consent-compliance">consent checklist</a>, <a class="link" href="/guides/migration">migration playbook</a>, <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow-collision guide</a>, and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing-model guide</a> alongside the official links in each profile. Record the access date, plan, limits, add-ons, data retention, and cancellation terms; do not preserve a stale price claim in a procurement document.</p></article></section>
  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Shopify deliverability FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
